#### FCO
FCO (first class object) is the base object.

Contains those specs which describe in the mission.
Identifies, as a set, the devices available to the mission.
There should be a constraint which ensures that all 'required' resources are 'available'.

#### Language Folder
The stereotypical objects, located in this language folder, can be considered as classes.

The mission goals specify the target parameters across the system.
The difficulty with mission goals is that they can be specific or general.
In this sample model they tend toward the more specific.
They define a few types of messages and the rates that those messages are sent/received from/by specific devices.

### Network Model

Model instances indicating the channels connecting physical devices.  

The network model will be augmented with provisioning as a cross-cut in the Mission-Model.

This simple model reflects the essential elements of a set of Android devices communicating with a central server.There are three variations on the nexus-7 device configuration A, B, and C.The instances for these three types are either created here {A1:A5, C1} or in the deployment model {B1:B4}.
The implementer must produce images at least 1024x1024 pixels in size AND with at least 24-bit RGB channels

### Mission Goals : Challenge Problem #1

#### Qualitative Goals

Location-data are generated by gps-devices.
This location-data can be saasm {required, optional, ?} as a goal.
The location-data goal can be set for the mission or by device.
(This is achieved by setting setting the saasm setting on the base mobile-device or on specific devices.)

These location-data are used to compose location-messages by mobile-devices.
The mobile-devices send the location-messages to the sa-server.
The sa-server distributes the location-messages to all mobile-devices.

#### Mission Goals : Challenge Problem #2

#### Quantitative Goals 

The rate that messages are created is set.
The rate which messages are received is specified as a range.
